column4: What are you mainly looking for feedback on?
column5: About how many words do you plan to bring to critique each week?
column6: What genre is your story? Please choose all that apply.
column7: What Content Warnings does your story have? Please choose all that apply. (We do not currently host sexually explicit/smut critique. Sorry. Fade to Black should be fine.)
column8: Would you prefer to work as a pair, a group of three, or four total people? Please choose all that apply.
column9: What feedback do you feel comfortable giving?
column10: How many words can you commit to critiquing each week per Housemate? Try to line this up with what you're willing to bring yourself.
column11: What genres would you like to critique? Please choose all that apply.
column12: What Content Warnings are you not comfortable reading and critiquing? Please choose all that apply.  (We do not currently host sexually explicit/smut critique. Sorry. Fade to Black should be fine.)
column13: If you were on a team and would like to work with them again, please list the members of your team and your team name. This question is optional.
column14: Is there anyone you would prefer NOT to work with again?
column15: I verify that I've read the Manuscript Critiques infographic above.
column16: Do you believe you've been in Critique Houses for 3+ months? I have records, but I'd like to verify against them.
column17: If you've been in Critique Houses for 3+ months, are currently active (currently signed up or participated in the last two months), and are launching a story this month, what is your Royal Road username and tentative title of that story? This question is optional.
column18: June is the Royal Road Community Magazine Contest. If you'd like to participate in that, and you'd be interested in a contest-focused critique house, please say so here. I'm trying to gauge interest so I can see how many special groups I'll probably need to make in JUNE.

column7: Gore and Excessive Violence, Traumatizing Content, Profanity, depends on the story.  one of the ones I'm thinking of has some profanity but not all that much; one of them has a pretty gory chapter but most of the rest of it isn't like that and the other story isn't gory. the gory chapter includes moderately graphic vivisection and off-page (but explicitly present) ritual cannibalism as part of a sort of human sacrifice thing but I don't think there's much else I'd call potentially traumatizing lmao.
column9: Reader's Feedback: I'm comfortable giving feedback as a reader.
column12: some gore/violence is fine but I'd prefer to not end up reading thousands of words of, like, splatterpunk levels of gore. I would also prefer not to critique works that have a lot of queerphobia depicted on-page.
